# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sip-telephony
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The **IP Multimedia Subsystem** or **IP Multimedia Core Network Subsystem** (**IMS**) is a standardized architectural framework for delivering IP-based multimedia services.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Historically, mobile phones have provided voice call services over a circuit-switched network, rather than over an IP-based packet-switched network.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Various VoIP technologies are available on smartphones; IMS offers a standardized protocol across different vendors.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] IMS was originally designed by the wireless standards body 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP), as a part of the vision for evolving mobile networks beyond GSM.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Its original formulation (3GPP Rel-5) represented an approach for delivering Internet services over GPRS.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] This vision was later updated by 3GPP, 3GPP2 and ETSI TISPAN by requiring support of networks other than GPRS, such as Wireless LAN, CDMA2000 and fixed lines.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] IMS uses IETF protocols wherever possible, e.g., the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP).
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] According to the 3GPP, IMS is not intended to standardize applications, but rather to aid the access of multimedia and voice applications from wireless and wireline terminals, i.e., to create a form of fixed-mobile convergence (FMC).
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] This is done by having a horizontal control layer that isolates the access network from the service layer.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] From a logical architecture perspective, services need not have their own control functions, as the control layer is a common horizontal layer.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] However, in implementation this does not necessarily map into greater reduced cost and complexity.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Alternative and overlapping technologies for access and provisioning of services across wired and wireless networks include combinations of Generic Access Network, softswitches and "naked" SIP.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Since it is becoming increasingly easier to access content and contacts using mechanisms outside the control of traditional wireless/fixed operators, the interest of IMS is being challenged.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] RCS also further added Presence/EAB (enhanced address book) functionality.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Some operators opposed IMS because it was seen as complex and expensive.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] In response, a cut-down version of IMS—enough of IMS to support voice and SMS over the LTE network—was defined and standardized in 2010 as Voice over LTE (VoLTE).
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Each of the functions in the diagram is explained below.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The IP multimedia core network subsystem is a collection of different functions, linked by standardized interfaces, which grouped form one IMS administrative network.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] A function is not a node (hardware box): An implementer is free to combine two functions in one node, or to split a single function into two or more nodes.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Each node can also be present multiple times in a single network, for dimensioning, load balancing or organizational issues.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The user can connect to IMS in various ways, most of which use the standard IP.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] IMS terminals (such as mobile phones, personal digital assistants (PDAs) and computers) can register directly on IMS, even when they are roaming in another network or country (the visited network).
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The only requirement is that they can use IP and run SIP user agents.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Fixed access (e.g., digital subscriber line (DSL), cable modems, Ethernet, FTTx), mobile access (e.g.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] 5G NR, LTE, W-CDMA, CDMA2000, GSM, GPRS) and wireless access (e.g., WLAN, WiMAX) are all supported.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Other phone systems like plain old telephone service (POTS—the old analogue telephones), H.323 and non IMS-compatible systems, are supported through gateways.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] A *subscriber location function* (SLF) is needed to map user addresses when multiple HSSs are used.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The HSS subscriber database contains the IMPU, IMPI, IMSI, MSISDN, subscriber service profiles, service triggers, and other information.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Several roles of SIP servers or proxies, collectively called Call Session Control Function (CSCF), are used to process SIP signaling packets in the IMS.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] SIP Application servers (AS) host and execute services, and interface with the S-CSCF using SIP.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] An example of an application server that is being developed in 3GPP is the Voice call continuity Function (VCC Server).
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Depending on the actual service, the AS can operate in SIP proxy mode, SIP UA (user agent) mode or SIP B2BUA mode.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] An AS can be located in the home network or in an external third-party network.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] If located in the home network, it can query the HSS with the Diameter Sh or Si interfaces (for a SIP-AS).
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The AS-ILCM (Application Server - Incoming Leg Control Model) and AS-OLCM (Application Server - Outgoing Leg Control Model) store transaction state, and may optionally store session state depending on the specific service being executed.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The AS-ILCM interfaces to the S-CSCF (ILCM) for an incoming leg and the AS-OLCM interfaces to the S-CSCF (OLCM) for an outgoing leg.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Application Logic provides the service(s) and interacts between the AS-ILCM and AS-OLCM.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Public Service Identities (PSI) are identities that identify services, which are hosted by application servers.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] As user identities, PSI takes the form of either a SIP or Tel URI.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The *Media Resource Function* (MRF) provides media related functions such as media manipulation (e.g. voice stream mixing) and playing of tones and announcements.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Each MRF is further divided into a *media resource function controller* (MRFC) and a *media resource function processor* (MRFP).
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The *Media Resource Broker* (MRB) is a functional entity that is responsible for both collection of appropriate published MRF information and supplying of appropriate MRF information to consuming entities such as the AS.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] A *Breakout Gateway Control Function* (BGCF) is a SIP proxy which processes requests for routing from an S-CSCF when the S-CSCF has determined that the session cannot be routed using DNS or ENUM/DNS.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] It includes routing functionality based on telephone numbers.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] A PSTN/CS gateway interfaces with PSTN circuit switched (CS) networks.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] For signalling, CS networks use ISDN User Part (ISUP) (or BICC) over Message Transfer Part (MTP), while IMS uses SIP over IP.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] For media, CS networks use Pulse-code modulation (PCM), while IMS uses Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP).
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Media Resources are those components that operate on the media plane and are under the control of IMS core functions.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] An NGN interconnection mode can be direct or indirect.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Direct interconnection refers to the interconnection between two network domains without any intermediate network domain.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Indirect interconnection at one layer refers to the interconnection between two network domains with one or more intermediate network domain(s) acting as transit networks.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The intermediate network domain(s) provide(s) transit functionality to the two other network domains.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Different interconnection modes may be used for carrying service layer signalling and media traffic.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Offline charging is applied to users who pay for their services periodically (e.g., at the end of the month).
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Online charging, also known as credit-based charging, is used for prepaid services, or real-time credit control of postpaid services.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Both may be applied to the same session.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] IMS-based PES (PSTN Emulation System) provides IP networks services to analog devices.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] IMS-based PES allows non-IMS devices to appear to IMS as normal SIP users.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Both A-MGW and VGW are unaware of the services.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] They only relay call control signalling to and from the PSTN terminal.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Session control and handling is done by IMS components.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] One of the most important features of IMS, that of allowing for a SIP application to be dynamically and differentially (based on the user's profile) triggered, is implemented as a filter-and-redirect signalling mechanism in the S-CSCF.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] The S-CSCF might apply filter criteria to determine the need to forward SIP requests to AS.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Services for the originating party will be applied in the originating network, while the services for the terminating party will be applied in the terminating network, all in the respective S-CSCFs.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] An **initial filter criteria** (iFC) is an XML-based format used for describing control logic. iFCs represent a provisioned subscription of a user to an application.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] It is envisaged that security defined in TS 33.203 may not be available for a while especially because of the lack of USIM/ISIM interfaces and prevalence of devices that support IPv4.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] For this situation, to provide some protection against the most significant threats, 3GPP defines some security mechanisms, which are informally known as "early IMS security," in TR33.978.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] This mechanism relies on the authentication performed during the network attachment procedures, which binds between the user's profile and its IP address.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] This mechanism is also weak because the signaling is not protected on the user–network interface.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] CableLabs in PacketCable 2.0, which adopted also the IMS architecture but has no USIM/ISIM capabilities in their terminals, published deltas to the 3GPP specifications where the Digest-MD5 is a valid authentication option.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Later on, TISPAN also did a similar effort given their fixed networks scopes, although the procedures are different.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] To compensate for the lack of IPsec capabilities, TLS has been added as an option for securing the Gm interface.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Later 3GPP Releases have included the Digest-MD5 method, towards a Common-IMS platform, yet in its own and again different approach.
[src:sip-telephony/ip-multimedia-subsystem] Although all 3 variants of Digest-MD5 authentication have the same functionality and are the same from the IMS terminal's perspective, the implementations on the Cx interface between the S-CSCF and the HSS are different.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] A **session border controller** (**SBC**) is a network element deployed to protect SIP-based VoIP networks.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Early deployments of SBCs were focused on the borders between two service provider networks in a peering environment.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] This role has since expanded to include significant deployments between a service provider's access network and its backbone network, providing service to residential and/or enterprise customers.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The term "session" refers to a communication between two or more parties – in the context of telephony, this would be a call.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Each call consists of one or more call signaling message exchanges that control the call, and one or more call media streams which carry the call's audio, video, or other data along with information of call statistics and quality.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Together, these streams make up a session.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] It is the job of a session border controller to exert influence over the data flows of sessions.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The term "border" refers to a point of demarcation between one part of a network and another.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] As a simple example, at the edge of a corporate network, a firewall demarcates the local network (inside the corporation) from the rest of the Internet (outside the corporation).
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] A more complex example is that of a large corporation where different departments have security needs for each location and perhaps for each kind of data.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In this case, filtering routers or other network elements are used to control the flow of data streams.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] It is the job of a session border controller to assist policy administrators in managing the flow of session data across these borders.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The term "controller" refers to the influence that session border controllers have on the data streams that comprise sessions, as they traverse borders between one part of a network and another.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Additionally, session border controllers often provide measurement, access control, and data conversion facilities for the calls they control.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] With the advent of WebRTC some SBCs have also assumed the role of SIP to WebRTC Gateway and translate SIP.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] While no one signalling protocol is mandated by the WebRTC specifications, SIP over WebSockets (RFC 7118) is often used partially due to the applicability of SIP to most of the envisaged communication scenarios as well as the availability of open source software such as JsSIP.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In such a case the SBC acts as a gateway between the WebRTC applications and SIP end points.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] SBCs are inserted into the signaling and/or media paths between calling and called parties in a VoIP call, predominantly those using the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), H.323, and MGCP call-signaling protocols.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In many cases the SBC hides the network topology and protects the service provider or enterprise packet networks.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The SBC terminates an inbound call and initiates the second call leg to the destination party.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In technical terms, when used with the SIP protocol, this defines a back-to-back user agent (B2BUA).
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The effect of this behavior is that not only the signaling traffic, but also the media traffic (voice, video) is controlled by the SBC.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In cases where the SBC does not have the capability to provide media services, SBCs are also able to redirect media traffic to a different element elsewhere in the network, for recording, generation of music-on-hold, or other media-related purposes.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Conversely, without an SBC, the media traffic travels directly between the endpoints, without the in-network call signaling elements having control over their path.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In other cases, the SBC simply modifies the stream of call control (signaling) data involved in each call, perhaps limiting the kinds of calls that can be conducted, changing the codec choices, and so on.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Ultimately, SBCs allow the network operators to manage the calls that are made on their networks, fix or change protocols and protocol syntax to achieve interoperability, and also overcome some of the problems that firewalls and network address translators (NATs) present for VoIP calls.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] To show the operation of an SBC, one can compare a simple call establishment sequence with a call establishment sequence with an SBC.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In the simplest session establishment sequence with only one proxy between the user agents the proxy’s task is to identify the callee’s location and forward the request to it.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The proxy also adds a Via header with its own address to indicate the path that the response should traverse.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The proxy does not change any dialog identification information present in the message such as the tag in the From header, the Call-Id or the Cseq.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Proxies also do not alter any information in the SIP message bodies.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Note that during the session initiation phase the user agents exchange SIP messages with the SDP bodies that include addresses at which the agents expect the media traffic.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] After successfully finishing the session initiation phase the user agents can exchange the media traffic directly between each other without the involvement of the proxy.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] SBCs are designed for many applications and are used by operators and enterprises to achieve a variety of goals.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Even the same SBC implementation might act differently depending on its configuration and the use case.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Hence, it is not easily possible to describe an exact SBC behavior that would apply to all SBC implementations.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In general it is possible to identify certain features that are common to SBCs.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] For example, most SBCs are implemented as back-to-back user agent.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] A B2BUA is a proxy-like server that splits a SIP transaction in two call legs: on the side facing the user agent client (UAC), it acts as server, on the side facing user agent server (UAS) it acts as a client.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] While a proxy usually keeps only state information related to active transactions, B2BUAs keep state information about active dialogs, e.g., calls.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] That is, once a proxy receives a SIP request it will save some state information.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Once the transaction is over, e.g., after receiving a response, the state information will soon after be deleted.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] A B2BUA will maintain state information for active calls and only delete this information once the call is terminated.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] When an SBC is included in the call path, the SBC acts as a B2BUA that behaves as a user agent server towards the caller and as user agent client towards the callee.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In this sense, the SBC actually terminates that call that was generated by the caller and starts a new call towards the callee.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The INVITE message sent by the SBC contains no longer a clear reference to the caller.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The INVITE sent by the SBC to the proxy includes Via and Contact headers that point to the SBC itself and not the caller.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] SBCs often also manipulate the dialog identification information listed in the Call-Id and From tag.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Further, in case the SBC is configured to also control the media traffic then the SBC also changes the media addressing information included in the c and m lines of the SDP body.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Thereby, not only will all SIP messages traverse the SBC but also all audio and video packets.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] As the INVITE sent by the SBC establishes a new dialog, the SBC also manipulates the message sequence number (CSeq) as well the Max-Forwards value.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Note that the list of header manipulations listed here is only a subset of the possible changes that an SBC might introduce to a SIP message.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Furthermore, some SBCs might not do all of the listed manipulations.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] If the SBC is not expected to control the media traffic then there might be no need to change anything in the SDP body.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Some SBCs do not change the dialog identification information and others might even not change the addressing information.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] SBCs are often used by corporations along with firewalls and intrusion prevention systems (IPS) to enable VoIP calls to and from a protected enterprise network.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] VoIP service providers use SBCs to allow the use of VoIP protocols from private networks with Internet connections using NAT, and also to implement strong security measures that are necessary to maintain a high quality of service.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] SBCs also replace the function of application-level gateways.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In larger enterprises, SBCs can also be used in conjunction with SIP trunks to provide call control and make routing/policy decisions on how calls are routed through the LAN/WAN.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] There are often tremendous cost savings associated with routing traffic through the internal IP networks of an enterprise, rather than routing calls through a traditional circuit-switched phone network.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Additionally, some SBCs can allow VoIP calls to be set up between two phones using different VoIP signaling protocols (e.g., SIP, H.323, Megaco/MGCP) as well as performing transcoding of the media stream when different codecs are in use.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Most SBCs also provide firewall features for VoIP traffic (denial of service protection, call filtering, bandwidth management).
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Protocol normalization and header manipulation is also commonly provided by SBCs, enabling communication between different vendors and networks.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] From an IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS) or 3GPP (3rd Generation Partnership Project) architecture perspective, the SBC is the integration of the P-CSCF and IMS-ALG at the signaling plane and the IMS Access Gateway at the media plane on the access side.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] On the interconnect side, the SBC maps to the IBCF, IWF at the signaling plane and TrGW (Transition Gateway) at the media plane.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] From an IMS/TISPAN architecture perspective, the SBC is the integration of the P-CSCF and C-BGF functions on the access side, and the IBCF, IWF, THIG, and I-BGF functions on the peering side.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Some SBCs can be "decomposed", meaning the signaling functions can be located on a separate hardware platform than the media relay functions – in other words the P-CSCF can be separated from the C-BGF, or the IBCF/IWF can be separated from the I-BGF functions physically.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Standards-based protocol, such as the H.248 Ia profile, can be used by the signaling platform to control the media one while a few SBCs use proprietary protocols.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] For example, should call control remain with Alice and Bob (two callers), or should call control be shared with the operators of all the IP networks involved in connecting Alice and Bob's VoIP phones together.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The debate of this point was vigorous, almost religious, in nature.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Those who wanted unfettered control in the endpoints only, were also greatly frustrated by the various realities of modern networks, such as firewalls and filtering/throttling.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] On the other side, network operators are typically concerned about overall network performance, interoperability and quality, and want to ensure it is secure.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Lawful intercept is governed in America by the Communications Assistance for Law Enforcement Act (CALEA).
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] An SBC may provide session media (usually RTP) and signaling (often SIP) wiretap services, which can be used by providers to enforce requests for the lawful interception of network sessions.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Standards for the interception of such services are provided by ATIS, TIA, CableLabs and ETSI, among others.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] According to Jonathan Rosenberg, the author of RFC 3261 (SIP) and numerous other related RFCs, Dynamicsoft developed the first working SBC in conjunction with Aravox, but the product never truly gained marketshare.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Newport Networks was the first to have an IPO on the London Stock Exchange's AIM in May 2004 (NNG), while Cisco has been publicly traded since 1990.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Acme Packet followed in October 2006 by floating on the NASDAQ.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] With the field narrowed by acquisition, NexTone merged with Reefpoint becoming Nextpoint, which was subsequently acquired in 2008 by Genband.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] At this same time, there emerged the "integrated" SBC where the border control function was integrated into another edge device.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] In 2009, Ingate Systems' Firewall became the first SBC to earn certification from ICSA Labs, a milestone in certifying the VoIP security capabilities of an SBC.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] The continuing growth of VoIP networks pushes SBCs further to the edge, mandating adaptation in capacity and complexity.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] As the VoIP network grows and traffic volume increases, more and more sessions are passing through SBC.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Vendors are addressing these new scale requirements in a variety of ways.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Some have developed separate, load balancing systems to sit in front of SBC clusters.
[src:sip-telephony/session-border-controller] Others, have developed new architectures using the latest generation chipsets offering higher performance SBCs and scalability using service cards.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] The **Session Description Protocol** (**SDP**) is a format for describing multimedia communication sessions for the purposes of announcement and invitation.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Its predominant use is in support of streaming media applications, such as voice over IP (VoIP) and video conferencing.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] SDP does not deliver any media streams itself but is used between endpoints for negotiation of network metrics, media types, and other associated properties.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] The set of properties and parameters is called a *session profile*.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] SDP is extensible for the support of new media types and formats.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] SDP was originally a component of the Session Announcement Protocol (SAP), but found other uses in conjunction with the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP), the Real-time Streaming Protocol (RTSP), Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), and as a standalone protocol for describing multicast sessions.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] The IETF published the original specification as a Proposed Standard in April 1998 (RFC 2327).
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Revised specifications were released in 2006 (RFC 4566), and in 2021 (RFC 8866).
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] The Session Description Protocol describes a session as a group of fields in a text-based format, one field per line.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Where `<character>` is a single case-sensitive character and `<value>` is structured text in a format that depends on the character.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed immediately to either side of the equal sign.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Session descriptions consist of three sections: session, timing, and media descriptions.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Each description may contain multiple timing and media descriptions.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Names are only unique within the associated syntactic construct.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Below is a sample session description from RFC 4566.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] This session is originated by the user "jdoe", at IPv4 address 10.47.16.5.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Its name is "SDP Seminar" and extended session information ("A Seminar on the session description protocol") is included along with a link for additional information and an email address to contact the responsible party, Jane Doe.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] This session is specified to last for two hours using NTP timestamps, with a connection address (which indicates the address clients must connect to or — when a multicast address is provided, as it is here — subscribe to) specified as IPv4 224.2.17.12 with a TTL of 127.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Recipients of this session description are instructed to only receive media.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Two media descriptions are provided, both using RTP Audio Video Profile.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] The first is an audio stream on port 49170 using RTP/AVP payload type 0 (defined by RFC 3551 as PCMU), and the second is a video stream on port 51372 using RTP/AVP payload type 99 (defined as "dynamic").
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Finally, an attribute is included which maps RTP/AVP payload type 99 to format h263-1998 with a 90 kHz clock rate.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] RTCP ports for the audio and video streams of 49171 and 51373, respectively, are implied.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] The SDP specification is purely a format for session description.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] It is intended to be distributed over different transport protocols as necessary, including SAP, SIP, and RTSP.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] SDP could even be transmitted by email or as an HTTP payload.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] SDP uses attributes to extend the core protocol.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Attributes can appear within the Session or Media sections and are scoped accordingly as *session-level* or *media-level*.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] New attributes are added to the standard occasionally through registration with IANA.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] The parameters *v*, *s*, and *o* are mandatory, must not be empty, and should be UTF-8-encoded.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] They are used as identifiers and are not intended to be displayed to users.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] A few other attributes are also present in the example, either as a session-level attribute (such as the attribute in property form *a=recvonly*), or as a media-level attribute (such as the attribute in value form *a=rtpmap:99 h263-1998/90000* for the video in the example).
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Absolute times are represented in Network Time Protocol (NTP) format (the number of seconds since 1900).
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] If the stop time is 0 then the session is *unbounded*.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] If the start time is also zero then the session is considered *permanent*.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Unbounded and permanent sessions are discouraged but not prohibited.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Intervals can be represented with NTP times or in typed time: a value and time units (days: *d*, hours: *h*, minutes: *m* and seconds: *s*) sequence.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] When repeat times are specified, the start time of each repetition may need to be adjusted to compensate for daylight saving time changes so that it will occur at the same local time in a specific time zone throughout the period between the start time and the stop time.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] All these offsets are relative to the start time, they are not cumulative.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] NTP supports this with field *z*, which indicates a series of pairs whose first item is the NTP absolute time when a daylight adjustment will occur, and the second item indicates the offset to apply relative to the absolute times computed with the field *r*.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] For example, if a daylight adjustment will subtract 1 hour on 31 October 2010 at 3 am UTC (i.e.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] If the weekly 1-hour session was repeated every Sunday for one full year, i.e. from Sunday 1 August 2010 3 am UTC to Sunday 26 June 2011 4 am UTC (stop time of the last repeat, i.e.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] As SDP announcements for repeated sessions should not be made to cover very long periods exceeding a few years, the number of daylight adjustments to include in the z= parameter should remain small.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] Sessions may be repeated irregularly over a week but scheduled the same way for all weeks in the period, by adding more tuples in the *r* parameter.
[src:sip-telephony/session-description-protocol] The SDP protocol does not support repeating sessions monthly and yearly schedules with such simple repeat times, because they are irregularly spaced in time; instead, additional *t*/*r* tuples may be supplied for each month or year.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The **Session Initiation Protocol** (**SIP**) is a signaling protocol used for initiating, maintaining, modifying, and terminating communication sessions that involve multimedia elements such as voice, video, and messaging.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] It operates at the application layer of the Internet protocol suite and is widely used in Internet telephony, private IP-based telephone systems, and mobile communication over LTE networks through VoLTE.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is a text-based protocol modeled on the structure of HTTP and SMTP, enabling interoperability and integration with other Internet applications.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] It provides mechanisms for user location, session setup, and session management, making it a foundational component of modern IP multimedia systems.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The protocol defines the specific format of messages exchanged and the sequence of communications for cooperation of the participants.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is a text-based protocol, incorporating many elements of the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) and the Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] A call established with SIP may consist of multiple media streams, but no separate streams are required for applications, such as text messaging, that exchange data as payload in the SIP message.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP works in conjunction with several other protocols that specify and carry the session media.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Most commonly, media type and parameter negotiation and media setup are performed with the Session Description Protocol (SDP), which is carried as payload in SIP messages.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is designed to be independent of the underlying transport layer protocol and can be used with the User Datagram Protocol (UDP), the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), and the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] For secure transmissions of SIP messages over insecure network links, the protocol may be encrypted with Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] For the transmission of media streams (voice, video) the SDP payload carried in SIP messages typically employs the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) or the Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP was originally designed by Mark Handley, Henning Schulzrinne, Eve Schooler and Jonathan Rosenberg in 1996 to facilitate establishing multicast multimedia sessions on the Mbone.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The protocol was standardized as RFC 2543 in 1999.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] In November 2000, SIP was accepted as a 3GPP signaling protocol and permanent element of the IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS) architecture for IP-based streaming multimedia services in cellular networks.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] In June 2002 the specification was revised in RFC 3261 and various extensions and clarifications have been published since.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP was designed to provide a signaling and call setup protocol for IP-based communications supporting the call processing functions and features present in the public switched telephone network (PSTN) with a vision of supporting new multimedia applications.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] It has been extended for video conferencing, streaming media distribution, instant messaging, presence information, file transfer, Internet fax and online games.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is distinguished by its proponents for having roots in the Internet community rather than in the telecommunications industry.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP has been standardized primarily by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF), while other protocols, such as H.323, have traditionally been associated with the International Telecommunication Union (ITU).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is only involved in the signaling operations of a media communication session and is primarily used to set up and terminate voice or video calls.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP can be used to establish two-party (unicast) or multiparty (multicast) sessions.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] It also allows modification of existing calls.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The modification can involve changing addresses or ports, inviting more participants, and adding or deleting media streams.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP has also found applications in messaging applications, such as instant messaging, and event subscription and notification.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP works in conjunction with several other protocols that specify the media format and coding and that carry the media once the call is set up.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] For call setup, the body of a SIP message contains a Session Description Protocol (SDP) data unit, which specifies the media format, codec and media communication protocol.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Voice and video media streams are typically carried between the terminals using the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) or Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Every resource of a SIP network, such as user agents, call routers, and voicemail boxes, are identified by a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The syntax of the URI follows the general standard syntax also used in Web services and e-mail.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The URI scheme used for SIP is *sip* and a typical SIP URI has the form *sip:username@domainname* or *sip:username@hostport*, where *domainname* requires DNS SRV records to locate the servers for SIP domain while *hostport* can be an IP address or a fully qualified domain name of the host and port.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] If secure transmission is required, the scheme *sips* is used.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP employs design elements similar to the HTTP request and response transaction model.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Each transaction consists of a client request that invokes a particular method or function on the server and at least one response.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP reuses most of the header fields, encoding rules and status codes of HTTP, providing a readable text-based format.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP can be carried by several transport layer protocols including Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), User Datagram Protocol (UDP), and Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP clients typically use TCP or UDP on port numbers 5060 or 5061 for SIP traffic to servers and other endpoints.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Port 5060 is commonly used for non-encrypted signaling traffic whereas port 5061 is typically used for traffic encrypted with Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP-based telephony networks often implement call processing features of Signaling System 7 (SS7), for which special SIP protocol extensions exist, although the two protocols themselves are very different.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SS7 is a centralized protocol, characterized by a complex central network architecture and dumb endpoints (traditional telephone handsets).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is a client-server protocol of equipotent peers.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP features are implemented in the communicating endpoints, while the traditional SS7 architecture is in use only between switching centers.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The network elements that use the Session Initiation Protocol for communication are called *SIP user agents*.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Each *user agent* (UA) performs the function of a *user agent client* (UAC) when it is requesting a service function, and that of a *user agent server* (UAS) when responding to a request.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Thus, any two SIP endpoints may in principle operate without any intervening SIP infrastructure.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] However, for network operational reasons, for provisioning public services to users, and for directory services, SIP defines several specific types of network server elements.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Each of these service elements also communicates within the client-server model implemented in user agent clients and servers.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] A user agent is a logical network endpoint that sends or receives SIP messages and manages SIP sessions.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] User agents have client and server components.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The user agent client (UAC) sends SIP requests.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The user agent server (UAS) receives requests and returns a SIP response.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Unlike other network protocols that fix the roles of client and server, e.g., in HTTP, in which a web browser only acts as a client, and never as a server, SIP requires both peers to implement both roles.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The roles of UAC and UAS only last for the duration of a SIP transaction.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] A SIP phone is an IP phone that implements client and server functions of a SIP user agent and provides the traditional call functions of a telephone, such as dial, answer, reject, call hold, and call transfer.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP phones may be implemented as a hardware device or as a softphone.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] As vendors increasingly implement SIP as a standard telephony platform, the distinction between hardware-based and software-based SIP phones is blurred and SIP elements are implemented in the basic firmware functions of many IP-capable communications devices such as smartphones.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] In SIP, as in HTTP, the user agent may identify itself using a message header field (*User-Agent*), containing a text description of the software, hardware, or the product name.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The user agent field is sent in request messages, which means that the receiving SIP server can evaluate this information to perform device-specific configuration or feature activation.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Operators of SIP network elements sometimes store this information in customer account portals, where it can be useful in diagnosing SIP compatibility problems or in the display of service status.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] A proxy server is a network server with UAC and UAS components that functions as an intermediary entity for the purpose of performing requests on behalf of other network elements.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] A proxy server primarily plays the role of call routing; it sends SIP requests to another entity closer to the destination.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Proxies are also useful for enforcing policy, such as for determining whether a user is allowed to make a call.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] A proxy interprets, and, if necessary, rewrites specific parts of a request message before forwarding it.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP proxy servers that route messages to more than one destination are called forking proxies.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The forking of a SIP request establishes multiple dialogs from the single request.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Thus, a call may be answered from one of multiple SIP endpoints.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] For identification of multiple dialogs, each dialog has an identifier with contributions from both endpoints.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] A redirect server is a user agent server that generates 3xx (redirection) responses to requests it receives, directing the client to contact an alternate set of URIs.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] A redirect server allows proxy servers to direct SIP session invitations to external domains.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] A registrar is a SIP endpoint that provides a location service.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] It accepts REGISTER requests, recording the address and other parameters from the user agent.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] For subsequent requests, it provides an essential means to locate possible communication peers on the network.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The location service links one or more IP addresses to the SIP URI of the registering agent.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Multiple user agents may register for the same URI, with the result that all registered user agents receive the calls to the URI.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP registrars are logical elements and are often co-located with SIP proxies.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] To improve network scalability, location services may instead be located with a redirect server.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Session border controllers (SBCs) serve as middleboxes between user agents and SIP servers for various types of functions, including network topology hiding and assistance in NAT traversal.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SBCs are an independently engineered solution and are not mentioned in the SIP RFC.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Gateways can be used to interconnect a SIP network to other networks, such as the PSTN, which use different protocols or technologies.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is a text-based protocol with syntax similar to that of HTTP.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] There are two different types of SIP messages: requests and responses.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The first line of a request has a *method*, defining the nature of the request, and a Request-URI, indicating where the request should be sent.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The first line of a response has a *response code*.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Requests initiate a functionality of the protocol.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] They are sent by a user agent client to the server and are answered with one or more SIP responses, which return a result code of the transaction, and generally indicate the success, failure, or other state of the transaction.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Responses are sent by the user agent server indicating the result of a received request.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP defines a transaction mechanism to control the exchanges between participants and deliver messages reliably.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] A transaction is a state of a session, which is controlled by various timers.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Client transactions send requests and server transactions respond to those requests with one or more responses.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The responses may include provisional responses with a response code in the form *1xx*, and one or multiple final responses (2xx – 6xx).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Transactions are further categorized as either type *invite* or type *non-invite*.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Invite transactions differ in that they can establish a long-running conversation, referred to as a *dialog* in SIP, and so include an acknowledgment (ACK) of any non-failing final response, e.g., *200 OK*.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The Session Initiation Protocol for Instant Messaging and Presence Leveraging Extensions (SIMPLE) is the SIP-based suite of standards for instant messaging and presence information.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Message Session Relay Protocol (MSRP) allows instant message sessions and file transfer.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The SIP developer community meets regularly at conferences organized by SIP Forum to test interoperability of SIP implementations.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The TTCN-3 test specification language, developed by a task force at ETSI (STF 196), is used for specifying conformance tests for SIP implementations.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] When developing SIP software or deploying a new SIP infrastructure, it is important to test the capability of servers and IP networks to handle certain call load: number of concurrent calls and number of calls per second.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP performance tester software is used to simulate SIP and RTP traffic to see if the server and IP network are stable under the call load.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The software measures performance indicators like answer delay, answer/seizure ratio, RTP jitter and packet loss, round-trip delay time.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP trunking is a similar marketing term preferred for when the service is used to simplify a telecom infrastructure by sharing the carrier access circuit for voice, data, and Internet traffic while removing the need for PRI circuits.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP-enabled video surveillance cameras can initiate calls to alert the operator of events, such as the motion of objects in a protected area.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is used in audio over IP for broadcasting applications where it provides an interoperable means for audio interfaces from different manufacturers to make connections with one another.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), Advanced Networking Technologies Division provides a public-domain Java implementation that serves as a reference implementation for the standard.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The implementation can work in proxy server or user agent scenarios and has been used in numerous commercial and research projects.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] It supports RFC 3261 in full and a number of extension RFCs including RFC 6665 (event notification) and RFC 3262 (reliable provisional responses).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Numerous other commercial and open-source SIP implementations exist.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP-I, Session Initiation Protocol with encapsulated ISUP, is a protocol used to create, modify, and terminate communication sessions based on ISUP using SIP and IP networks.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Services using SIP-I include voice, video telephony, fax and data.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP-I and SIP-T are two protocols with similar features, notably to allow ISUP messages to be transported over SIP networks.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] This preserves all of the detail available in the ISUP header.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIP-I was defined by the ITU-T, whereas SIP-T was defined by the IETF.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] Concerns about the security of calls via the public Internet have been addressed by encryption of the SIP protocol for secure transmission.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The URI scheme SIPS is used to mandate that SIP communication be secured with Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] SIPS URIs take the form sips:user@example.com.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] End-to-end encryption of SIP is only possible if there is a direct connection between communication endpoints.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] While a direct connection can be made via Peer-to-peer SIP or via a VPN between the endpoints, most SIP communication involves multiple hops, with the first hop being from a user agent to the user agent's ITSP.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] For the multiple-hop case, SIPS will only secure the first hop; the remaining hops will normally not be secured with TLS and the SIP communication will be insecure.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] In contrast, the HTTPS protocol provides end-to-end security as it is done with a direct connection and does not involve the notion of hops.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The media streams (audio and video), which are separate connections from the SIPS signaling stream, may be encrypted using SRTP.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] The key exchange for SRTP is performed with SDES (RFC 4568), or with ZRTP (RFC 6189).
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] When SDES is used, the keys will be transmitted via insecure SIP unless SIPS is used.
[src:sip-telephony/session-initiation-protocol] One may also add a MIKEY (RFC 3830) exchange to SIP to determine session keys for use with SRTP.
[src:sip-telephony/user-agent] On the Web, a **user agent** is a software agent responsible for retrieving and facilitating end-user interaction with Web content.
[src:sip-telephony/user-agent] This includes all web browsers, such as Google Chrome and Safari, some email clients, standalone download managers like youtube-dl, and other command-line utilities like cURL.
[src:sip-telephony/user-agent] The user agent is the client in a client–server system.
[src:sip-telephony/user-agent] The HTTP User-Agent header is intended to clearly identify the agent to the server.
[src:sip-telephony/user-agent] However, this header can be omitted or spoofed, so some websites use other detection methods.
